WEBVTT

00:02.731 --> 00:05.574
No, sir. No, sir. I must have been before my time or 
after.

00:11.439 --> 00:11.960
Let's see. Did you all go to any campus dances? No, 
sir. As a matter of fact, Richard and I never did go

00:18.666 --> 00:22.109
to dance. See, I don't dance. I'm a teetotaler. I 
don't drink and I don't smoke. I don't go to dances

00:28.976 --> 00:32.299
because my grandmother raised me, you see. She was 
really strict and she didn't want me to get mixed up

00:32.684 --> 00:42.956
with the wrong people and start drinking with them 
and all this. I share those practices with you. And

00:47.401 --> 00:57.072
then my wife was brought up with the Baptists in 
Beeville, and you know, the Baptists don't dance

00:47.401 --> 00:57.072
either. Now, there had been some veterans' 
temporary housing down here on this side of the

00:57.862 --> 01:06.810
football stadium. That had been removed by the 
time you all got here. There were some temporary,

01:10.383 --> 01:22.557
where G. Raleigh White Coliseum is now, there were 
some temporary veteran's houses in 46 and 47, but

01:10.383 --> 01:22.557
those were gone by the time y'all got here.

01:26.081 --> 01:35.732
As you are going on toward that major in animal 
husbandry, who did you turn to for advice and

01:26.081 --> 01:35.732
counsel? Who gave, who told you what courses to 
take? Nobody told me what courses to take, no.

01:44.948 --> 01:57.284
Rachel had a brother that was working for the BVL 
Experimental Station, and he was an animal

01:44.948 --> 01:57.284
husband and an agronomer, okay? And in 
conversations with him and the other two that were

01:57.304 --> 02:05.415
attending here,

02:06.796 --> 02:15.658
I was interested in agronomy, but then I was afraid 
that I would not be able to pass maybe the chemistry

02:17.157 --> 02:22.703
or the math that went along with it. So I had to 
select something that I knew I could pass. And so I

02:28.970 --> 02:35.557
started considering getting a liberal arts or a 
business. And business looked better. And so then

02:39.641 --> 02:47.029
because of my experiences and the work I used to do, 
I thought I wanted to major in marketing with a

02:47.482 --> 02:52.329
minor in English. Who advised you to do that? Well, 
to tell you the truth, nobody. Oh, okay. I took the

03:01.561 --> 03:04.025
catalog and I was going through it. If I want to 
major here, what question do I have to take? Can I

03:11.235 --> 03:12.136
pass them? I was looking back. hey, I was 32 years 
old, I was out of high school, and I was a high school

03:16.085 --> 03:20.470
dropout. So I had, there was some disadvantages 
there, but I wanted to be sure after, you know,

03:21.130 --> 03:34.064
getting rid of my house and furniture and so forth, 
and for me to flunk out again, no. I gotta make a go of

03:34.084 --> 03:39.169
it, and I made that decision myself, see. All 
right, now, as you began your senior year, When did

03:43.979 --> 03:46.783
you buy that ring? Oh, I didn't buy the ring. One of 
the brothers, Rachel's brothers that had already

03:51.490 --> 04:01.043
graduated, he was a petroleum engineer with 
Atlantic Refining. He was nice enough to buy my

04:03.547 --> 04:10.797
ring and get Rachel her ring. I want to tell you 
something, you won't believe it. I still have the

04:14.253 --> 04:15.254
ring. This is the original one. And I learned to 
take it off when I wash my hands or when I'm working,

04:17.577 --> 04:23.485
so it won't bleed. And then I take some India ink and 
I cover it, then I let it dry, and I take a damp rag and

04:24.566 --> 04:33.078
clean it off. So it still looks almost new. Yeah. 
And some people look at that, is that a new one? No. I

04:43.362 --> 04:44.523
didn't ask.

04:47.807 --> 04:58.878
My brother-in-law, his name was Alvino, Alvino 
Reyes, he told Rachel he paid $29.50 for this ring.

04:58.898 --> 04:59.479
Oh my, my. Believe it or not. Now, his son, he had a 
son that was handicapped, and I decided to return

05:01.922 --> 05:11.732
the favor. And I told him, I said, look Bubba, I want 
to pay for your record. Oh he was pleased. So I

05:22.038 --> 05:23.580
shelled out $175. I did that gladly really. But I 
don't know what that costs now. Do you have any ring

05:32.114 --> 05:33.756
stories? Have you ever lost your ring and found it 
in somebody? Or have you ever been somewhere on the

05:37.920 --> 05:42.485
other side of the world and somebody saw that Aggie 
ring? No, sir, I never lost it. I made sure that I put

05:46.209 --> 05:50.914
it in my pocket.

05:53.376 --> 05:57.801
Well, even to this day, people see my ring, they 
say, Hey, I just saw your ring. And before they

06:00.549 --> 06:02.992
could say anything, I went to whip out and meet 
them. And here we are. And right now, I'm retired,

06:05.255 --> 06:18.632
and I'm a volunteer at a cafeteria-style 
restaurant that belongs to the First Baptist

06:05.255 --> 06:18.632
Church back in San Antonio. And Southwestern Bell 
has a monster building just about two blocks away.

06:24.500 --> 06:28.024
I was on the Southwestern Bell board for 17 years. 
So there's a bunch of Aggies that are working there

06:29.236 --> 06:35.062
and they come over there and eat. And I'll bust 
tables you know and do arching in. And when I fill up

06:40.427 --> 06:45.853
their glasses with tea, it starts again. So I greet 
them. Hi Aggie. And people turn around. Yes sir,

06:52.799 --> 06:58.365
that ring touches something. I wear this one, 
that's my Masonic ring. And some guy said, look,

07:02.923 --> 07:06.989
I'm wearing the same kind of ring you've got. But 
that's, I don't recall going somewhere in, you

07:08.651 --> 07:27.576
know, a way, or just nothing of any importance. 
that I know of that I have for you. All right, let's

07:33.707 --> 07:34.367
see. Your senior year, you mention in here that 
your son starts school and your wife got sick. Oh,

07:43.776 --> 07:44.036
yeah. And so you had to double up and you moved to a 
dormitory. What was it like for an old man to live

