suit of clothes. I can't pay you. But as soon as I get 
a job, I'll pay you." He said, ah, bonk. He took over

10:44.597 --> 10:45.598
there. I got a brand new dark blue suit. And he wrote 
something on there. It's this. And he gave it to me.

10:58.816 --> 11:00.719
Otherwise, I didn't have a suit of clothes. And so 
that's part of our graduation. and uh it was it was

11:05.935 --> 11:27.876
great all right as you walked across that stage 
that day what feelings did you have in your heart oh

11:05.935 --> 11:27.876
i said i was relieved of all the pressure i was 
living under and this kind of thing that uh you know

11:05.935 --> 11:27.876
uh You don't have to repeat this, but my wife had 
hemorrhoids. And one of the hemorrhoids had some

11:36.334 --> 11:49.929
kind of a knot in it or something that her doctor, 
Dr. Lancaster, said that this could be something

11:36.334 --> 11:49.929
bad, and I think we better get it out of the way. And 
so I had some health insurance with me. I can't

11:56.982 --> 11:59.124
remember the name, but they called him Tack. He had 
an office in Northgate, you know, T-A-C-K. And it

11:59.745 --> 12:10.537
was that coverage I had that got my wife at the 
hospital there in Bealeville. And she, I was, I was

12:11.778 --> 12:26.955
sending her the, I was getting, I was sending her 
$60 of my $120. And now, see, I was the guy and I was,

12:27.678 --> 12:38.309
my gross was $80 a month. And of course, for the end 
of the month came by, I didn't get paid at the end of

12:39.570 --> 12:44.875
the month. You had to wait about two weeks. So, and I 
was sending the whole check to them in New York. I

12:53.104 --> 12:57.448
says, listen, you living over there with your 
mother, recuperating? And I don't want to hear any

12:57.850 --> 13:02.497
of your sisters or brothers saying that you were a 
charity case. You pay your mama and you tell her

13:03.338 --> 13:12.631
that, look, this is all I've got, but I want to pay 
for my food and for Robert's food and whatever. So

13:13.493 --> 13:23.487
they wouldn't come later on and criticize me for 
leaving my wife over there and let her mother take

13:13.493 --> 13:23.487
care of her. As you were getting ready to graduate, 
what kind of preparation did you think A&M had

13:25.492 --> 13:36.828
given you for the real world? Well. How well 
prepared were you? I was prepared. And

13:46.382 --> 13:54.874
when I went for the job interviews, I would get uh, 
offers for out of state, out of town. And my wife had

14:01.161 --> 14:06.328
tap roots in San Antonio, New York, and she didn't 
want to move anywhere. I said, oh, good, you know.

14:10.152 --> 14:14.397
And, uh, so I said, well, I'd have to find something 
here in San Antonio. And, uh, she says, all right,

14:14.978 --> 14:18.402
um, oh. I said, let's see, uh, what the Lord wants to 
do with us and, uh, see if we'll go from here. So

14:25.381 --> 14:40.234
I looked around and I got this, the best job I had was 
working on it at Lackland, civilian position. And

14:41.556 --> 14:54.027
Lackland had a requirement that you had to know 
this and this and this and this, or one year of

14:41.556 --> 14:54.027
college. That's a snap. And this was a big 
operation. The training needs a vision. Because

15:00.731 --> 15:04.978
Lackland, at the time I was there, was like a little 
college. Oh, it was huge. And the trainees weren't

15:07.523 --> 15:11.008
in there for training. They had three training 
bases, one in Rome, New York, one in California,

15:11.529 --> 15:18.340
and then the one there in San Antonio. So they 
closed these other two and left Lackland. And they

15:22.857 --> 15:24.820
had a dental school. They had a police school. They 
had . So the division would make custom-made

15:28.385 --> 15:50.518
teaching aids,

15:28.385 --> 15:50.518
all kinds of manuals, instruction manuals, 
building ceremonies, and whatever the

15:28.385 --> 15:50.518
instructors wanted besides the language school. 
They had a language school where they would teach

15:51.545 --> 15:59.334
English to these foreign pilots. So someday, we 
would need them as our allies. And the trainees

16:02.438 --> 16:08.184
also made language trainers. You're familiar 
with a language trainer, where you're watching it

16:08.204 --> 16:11.508
and hearing it. And it was nice, and security. My 
wife was satisfied. Then I got the opportunity to

16:21.852 --> 16:34.491
go to Kelly Air Force Base and it was a little bit 
more responsibility and it was a better job.

16:37.596 --> 16:42.443
Since I had all this experience with parts for 
General Motors, We didn't have a buyer that could

16:43.199 --> 16:47.786
buy aircraft parts. So I got in there and they 
shipped me off to Fort Lee, Virginia. Six weeks in a

16:55.898 --> 17:04.531
preparatory school for buyers. And I came back. 
And let me see.

17:13.608 --> 17:24.601
I had gone to the office, and all of a sudden there 
was a dead silence. What happened? The news came on

17:26.143 --> 17:28.486
that President Kennedy had been shot. Oh, my God, 
this would have to happen. Well, anyway, I stayed

17:32.871 --> 17:41.421
all night at Kelly and worked up from a bar to a 
contracting officer. with a warrant and it

17:42.160 --> 18:00.941
was the General's approval and one from up in 
command level and I had no limitations and it was

17:42.160 --> 18:00.941
good until I retired. As you look back, what did A&M 
for you, what did A&M do well?

18:10.966 --> 18:20.079
So get a job, and when you got it, you worked on it to 
completion, and that it would be done right. And

18:21.201 --> 18:22.904
they wouldn't settle for anything else. And that 
stayed with me. And so in my work, I went from A to Z,

18:26.168 --> 18:35.522
so that if my supervisors ever Well, they couldn't 
question me because it was all right there, ready

18:36.346 --> 18:41.532
to go. And complete it to a successful end and don't 
mess around and do it right. If you had all of the

18:50.383 --> 19:00.134
people that were at A&M when you were here, if all of 
them were here today, which ones would you most

18:50.383 --> 19:00.134
want to thank? To what people from that time are you 
most grateful? Tom Putty. You see, maybe I

19:06.721 --> 19:21.027
shouldn't say this, and you don't have to, but when 
I applied to the employment office, there was an

19:06.721 --> 19:21.027
old gentleman, you know, he had a big hat like he was 
a retired rancher. And he says, I can't consider

19:22.390 --> 19:26.738
you for a job. He says, you're a veteran, and you're 
getting $120 a month. He says, I've got some kids

19:33.226 --> 19:37.911
coming out of high school that don't have a penny. 
He says, I've got to give them priority. So I can't

19:41.775 --> 19:46.159
offer you a job. Oh, boy, that's when I started. And 
I went to Chevrolet dealer Brian Carpenter. I got

19:54.688 --> 19:57.231
all the help I need. Well, how about part-time? 
Somebody take inventory or something. And I went

20:04.604 --> 20:06.246
to Caldwell, same way.

20:09.468 --> 20:10.650
I was just about to give up. So I went back to meet Mr. 
Putty. And he turned things around for me. And I

20:16.335 --> 20:18.837
said, hey, let's. Are there any teachers or 
advisors that you'd also want to thank? Any

20:24.002 --> 20:24.742
faculty? Any staff? Yes. One was my English 
professor, Mr., and then there was, I can't think

20:28.075 --> 20:38.686
of his name, but you remember Mr. Esten? C.K. 
Esten. Yeah, he used to, him, I had him for English.

20:45.473 --> 20:53.762
And

20:45.473 --> 20:53.762
he made me give an oral report, see? and he liked it. 
He came over and he put his arm around me and we were

20:55.329 --> 20:59.814
good friends from then on. And let's see, I'm 
trying to think.

21:07.281 --> 21:09.103
Those were the only two, sir. What is it that builds 
Aggie spirit? What causes those feelings? Well,

21:18.453 --> 21:21.336
in my experience, If I had something to do with 
another guy, he was an Aggie. And I let him know I was

21:29.019 --> 21:30.861
an Aggie, too. That friendship was good together, 
see? And I knew that any dealings I had or any

21:36.907 --> 21:47.638
assistance I needed from a fellow Aggie, that I 
would get it. That if my car broke down on the

21:48.459 --> 21:51.222
highway, which it did, A bunch of Aggies in the 
corner had stopped. What can I do to help you? Do you

21:56.565 --> 21:59.489
need a flat fixed or whatever? And I knew that there 
was a binding thing there between Aggies, and I

21:59.509 --> 22:18.019
knew that if I had to deal with another Aggie for 
whatever, I was in need, that I could expect some

21:59.509 --> 22:18.019
form of help. What causes the Aggies, though, to be 
helpful to each other?

22:27.925 --> 22:34.095
What is it that happens while they're in school 
here?

22:35.076 --> 22:35.937
It's hard to say. I mean, words fail me. If

22:39.202 --> 22:48.597
there's a place that's owned by an Aggie, If I let 
them know, hey, I'm an Aggie, he will drop the

22:49.471 --> 23:07.134
restriction and it's a way of getting in or getting 
to know the person. We're given help to achieve

23:08.196 --> 23:18.229
what I'm trying to get or go for, and I can expect 
friendship and help that I wouldn't get from

23:18.833 --> 23:23.721
somebody else that was not an Aggie. Let me give you 
a for instance. My brother Bert, I mean my

23:28.508 --> 23:40.887
brother-in-law Bert, he was a cattle auctioneer, 
and he had to go to Montana

23:28.508 --> 23:40.887
for a cattle sale. And it was dark, you know, He was a 
stranger up there. He didn't know nobody. When he

23:51.595 --> 23:56.981
goes to the stockyards, there was a bunch of Aggies 
over there, agricultural people. And when Bert

23:57.622 --> 24:07.152
went over there to meet him, and he found out that 
there were Aggies, you know, he changed the whole

23:57.622 --> 24:07.152
thing. Anything he needed, he got it, because 
those Aggies would help him. And Bertone says,

24:13.019 --> 24:19.327
that goes on everywhere, in civilian life and in 
the military. And my son, he goes back and forth,

24:20.188 --> 24:26.375
and he meets Aggies all over. And they all, a lot of 
them come here for legal advice.

24:34.685 --> 24:40.933
If you could advise the leaders of Texas A&M today, 
what advice would you give them?

24:46.347 --> 25:06.414
to continue

24:46.347 --> 25:06.414
and enlarge on the friendship and the camaraderie 
of all Aggies. I say that because Plurton

25:07.556 --> 25:14.245
Vandiver, he wanted to do away with the Corps. And I 
said, well, he's crazy. I said, the Morrill Act

25:17.219 --> 25:25.053
says A&M is going to be put up there because we need a 
school of agriculture. There was no other place.

25:27.156 --> 25:33.628
And in addition to that, it says there will be 
military training at that place. So Mr. Vandiver

25:33.648 --> 25:36.773
cannot do away with it. And we're going to have 
people like that, sir, that are going to stop

25:37.259 --> 25:43.848
certain traditions. And I want to tell those 
people, don't listen to that crap. I say, you keep

25:48.474 --> 25:55.644
this thing going, and it's the only one in the world 
that's like this, that I know of. And you keep that

25:57.026 --> 26:04.295
going, and then if there's hostilities come up, 
who's going to get the first call? A&M. So it

26:06.757 --> 26:14.188
behooves you to just make no changes and improve on 
it.

